import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>The LORD commands Moses and Aaron to take a census of the Kohathite clan, specifically those aged 30 to 50 for active tabernacle service. The age threshold of 30 prefigures Christ, who began his public ministry at age thirty (<a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 3:23'>Luke 3:23</a>), suggesting that full priestly service — the labor of carrying God's presence — is not for spiritual immaturity but for proven readiness.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Kohathites as a sub-clan of Levi are set apart for the most sacred service: carrying the holy objects of the Most Holy Place. This anticipates Christ as the one mediator who alone can bear divine holiness into direct contact with humanity (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Tim 2:5'>1 Tim 2:5</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 9:15'>Heb 9:15</a>), carrying God's presence from heaven's tabernacle to earth.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The service window of ages 30–50 designates men in their prime of strength and maturity. Christ's earthly ministry began at 30 and lasted approximately three years (<a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 3:23'>Luke 3:23</a>); his entire life was consecrated service, the perfect fulfillment of this appointed readiness that the age requirement symbolized.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Kohathites' work is described as <em>ʿăḇōdat qōḏeš haqqŏḏāšîm</em> — service of the holy of holies. Christ's high-priestly work is precisely this: entering the Most Holy Place not with animal blood but with his own, accomplishing eternal redemption (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 9:11-12'>Heb 9:11–12</a>).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Aaron and his sons must first cover the ark of the covenant with the veil before the Kohathites approach. The veil's role as intermediary covering points to the incarnation itself — the glory of God veiled in human flesh so that humanity could come near (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 1:14'>John 1:14</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Col 2:9'>Col 2:9</a>).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Over the veil covering the ark goes blue cloth (sky-color, heavenly) then a cover of dugong/badger hides — beauty within, plain without. The incarnate Christ appeared as an ordinary man outwardly (<a class='ref' data-ref='Isa 53:2'>Isa 53:2</a>, no attracting form), yet within dwelt the fullness of deity, the covenant presence veiled in humble flesh.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The table of the bread of the presence is wrapped in blue cloth; the bread (<em>leḥem pānîm</em>, bread of the face/presence) always before God is the perpetual nourishment of his people. Christ declares himself the true bread of life, the living Presence that sustains all who come to him (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 6:35'>John 6:35</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='John 6:51'>John 6:51</a>).</p>",
    "8": "<p>A crimson cloth covers the bread-table items, then the badger-skin outer cover. The crimson echoes sacrifice and blood — the very life of Christ poured out in atonement. The table of his body and blood (the Lord's Supper) now replaces the showbread table as the place of communal nourishment before God (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Cor 11:24-25'>1 Cor 11:24–25</a>).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The lampstand (<em>mənōrâ</em>) is wrapped in blue — the heavenly light — with all its utensils. Christ is the light of the world (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 8:12'>John 8:12</a>); the seven-branched lampstand prefigures the one who illuminates every person and fills the church with Spirit-fueled radiance (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 1:12-16'>Rev 1:12–16</a>).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The wrapped lampstand and its implements are placed on a carrying frame, borne by the Levites. The church as the body of Christ becomes the new lampstand (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 1:20'>Rev 1:20</a>), carrying his light into the world, each congregation a bearer of the light that belongs to Christ alone.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The gold incense altar is wrapped in blue cloth. The altar of incense represents intercessory prayer ascending to God (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 8:3-4'>Rev 8:3–4</a>). Christ fulfills this as the eternal intercessor, his fragrant sacrifice and ongoing intercession at the Father's right hand the ultimate incense altar (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 7:25'>Heb 7:25</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Rom 8:34'>Rom 8:34</a>).</p>",
    "12": "<p>All ministry instruments of service within the sanctuary are wrapped and covered for transport. Every implement finds its antitype in Christ's person and work — the tools of sacrifice, light, bread, and incense each pointing to dimensions of his one completed offering and ongoing ministry.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The ashes are removed from the bronze altar, which is spread with a purple cloth. The bronze altar, site of burnt offerings, typifies Calvary — the place of divine judgment on sin. Purple, the color of royalty, reminds us that the one sacrificed on that ultimate altar is the King of kings (<a class='ref' data-ref='Mark 15:17'>Mark 15:17</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 19:16'>Rev 19:16</a>).</p>",
    "14": "<p>All the bronze implements — fire pans, forks, shovels, basins, all utensils of the altar — are wrapped in badger skins. The multiplicity of sacrifice implements points to Christ's one all-sufficient sacrifice that renders all the daily, weekly, and festival offerings complete. He is both priest and sacrifice, officiant and altar (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 9:26'>Heb 9:26</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 10:12'>Heb 10:12</a>).</p>",
    "15": "<p>After Aaron and his sons cover the holy things, the Kohathites may carry them — but must not touch the holy things or they will die. Only Christ can bear the actual weight of God's holiness without destruction; he alone is the mediator who bridges infinite holiness and sinful humanity without perishing (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Tim 2:5'>1 Tim 2:5</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 7:26'>Heb 7:26</a>). Those who come to God must come through him.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Eleazar son of Aaron is charged with oversight of the tabernacle's entire operation — oil, incense, grain offering, anointing oil. As Aaron's successor, Eleazar prefigures Christ's high-priestly oversight of the new-covenant temple — his body the church — fueling its worship, intercession, and consecrated service (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Pet 2:25'>1 Pet 2:25</a>, where Christ is called <em>episkopos</em>).</p>",
    "17": "<p>God commands Moses and Aaron directly: do not let the tribe of Kohath be cut off from the Levites. God's passionate concern not to lose the carriers of his holiness reflects Christ's own declaration: 'All that the Father gives me will come to me, and whoever comes to me I will never cast out' (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 6:37'>John 6:37</a>).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The command 'do not cut off the Kohathites from the midst of the Levites' echoes the covenant promise that God's priestly servants will not be destroyed. Christ, the true and final High Priest, is indestructible — his priesthood permanent because he lives forever (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 7:16'>Heb 7:16</a>, <em>ζωὴ ἀκαταλύτου</em>, indestructible life).</p>",
    "19": "<p>Aaron and his sons must assign each Kohathite his specific task and load so they can approach the holy things and live. Christ similarly assigns each of his servants a specific calling and gifts within the body (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Cor 12:18'>1 Cor 12:18</a>), enabling them to serve without presumption or overreach, each sustained in their assigned place.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The Kohathites must not go in to look at the holy things even for a moment, lest they die. The instinct to look directly at unveiled divine glory is natural but fatal to sinners — only in Christ, the covering and mediator, can humanity truly see God and live (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 14:9'>John 14:9</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='2 Cor 4:6'>2 Cor 4:6</a>, glory seen in the face of Christ).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The census of the Gershonite clan extends the principle of organized, purposeful service to those who carry the fabric elements of the tabernacle. Christ's commission encompasses every kind of servant — not only those nearest the ark but all who labor in the outer courts of kingdom work (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 28:19-20'>Matt 28:19–20</a>).</p>",
    "22": "<p>Gershon's sons are also numbered from ages 30 to 50 — the same standard of mature readiness that applied to Kohath. Christ calls mature disciples into deliberate labor for God's dwelling, the church built not on enthusiasm alone but on seasoned, Spirit-formed character (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 4:12-13'>Eph 4:12–13</a>).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Gershonites are enlisted to serve in the <em>ṣāḇāʾ</em> (host/army) of the tent of meeting — the assembly of sacred labor. Christ gathers his people as a holy army serving God's new-covenant tabernacle; the church is described as both temple and army, built by and for the Lord of hosts (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 19:14'>Rev 19:14</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 2:21-22'>Eph 2:21–22</a>).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The Gershonite clans carry the tabernacle curtains, coverings, and hangings. The rich layered fabrics of the tabernacle — blue, purple, crimson, and fine linen — foreshadow the woven glory of Christ's person: his heavenly origin (blue), royal kingship (purple), sacrificial blood (crimson), and spotless humanity (white linen).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Gershon's specific burden includes the tabernacle's fabric curtains and the tent covering. The innermost linen veil was torn at Christ's death (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 27:51'>Matt 27:51</a>), making the curtain-bearing service of Gershon a perpetual symbol of the barrier that Christ would decisively breach — opening the way into God's presence for all who believe.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The courtyard hangings, gate screen, and all the cords belong to Gershon's care. The gate of the court — the entry point into the sacred precinct — prefigures Christ who declares himself the gate, the only entry into God's presence and salvation (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 10:7-9'>John 10:7–9</a>).</p>",
    "27": "<p>All Gershonite transport must be at the direction of Aaron and his sons — authorized by the high priest. Christ, the great High Priest, is the one who assigns and authorizes all ministry; no one serves God rightly in the new covenant except through Christ's commissioning and sustaining authority (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 15:5'>John 15:5</a>).</p>",
    "28": "<p>Aaron's son Ithamar supervises the Gershonites. The line of priestly supervision runs through Aaron's family — anticipating the new-covenant High Priest Jesus Christ, Son of the Father, in whose name all ministry is conducted and from whom all spiritual oversight flows (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 3:6'>Heb 3:6</a>, Christ as Son over God's house).</p>",
    "29": "<p>The Merarite clan is now enrolled — those who carry the structural hardware of the tabernacle: boards, bars, pillars, bases, and pegs. Christ is the cornerstone upon whom the entire structure of God's dwelling rests; without him no spiritual building stands (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 2:20'>Eph 2:20</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='1 Pet 2:6'>1 Pet 2:6</a>).</p>",
    "30": "<p>Merari also serves from ages 30 to 50. The boards, bars, and bases of the tabernacle are unglamorous structural load — foundational and essential, invisible when the tent is standing. Christ's cross is the unglamorous structural load of salvation: hidden beneath religion's surface, yet the only thing holding up the entire edifice of redemption.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Merari's specific burden: the boards of the tabernacle, its bars, pillars, and bases. Boards of acacia overlaid in gold standing upright prefigure resurrection — earthy substance glorified. Christ is both the upright man who stood through death and the glorified one raised incorruptible (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Cor 15:42-44'>1 Cor 15:42–44</a>).</p>",
    "32": "<p>The pillars of the court, their bases, pegs, and cords — every structural component is named and assigned. The precision of God's ordering of the tabernacle skeleton prefigures Christ's meticulous knowledge of every member of his body; he names, orders, and sustains each joint and ligament of the church (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 4:16'>Eph 4:16</a>).</p>",
    "33": "<p>This is the service of the Merarite clans — all their service at the tent of meeting under Ithamar's supervision. The completeness of the assignment echoes Christ's own 'It is finished' (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 19:30'>John 19:30</a>, <em>tetelestai</em>) — the perfect execution of every assigned task in the service of God's dwelling on earth.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Moses, Aaron, and the leaders count the Kohathites aged 30 to 50: 2,750 men. The specific enumeration of those qualified for sacred service points to Christ who knows each of his own by name and has appointed their ministry — none are forgotten in the counting (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 10:3'>John 10:3</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 10:20'>Luke 10:20</a>).</p>",
    "35": "<p>All Kohathites who could enter service at the tent of meeting — enrolled by name. The naming of those enrolled in sacred service prefigures the book of life in which the names of Christ's redeemed are written — a roll call of those whom the Son knows, calls, and keeps (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 21:27'>Rev 21:27</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Phil 4:3'>Phil 4:3</a>).</p>",
    "36": "<p>The Kohathite count of 2,750 men reflects God's abundant provision for the carrying of his holiest objects. The sufficiency of qualified servants for God's work ultimately rests in Christ, who gives gifts to men and appoints apostles, prophets, evangelists, and pastor-teachers for the building up of the body (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 4:11'>Eph 4:11</a>).</p>",
    "37": "<p>Those Kohathites numbered were all who served at the tent of meeting, 'as the LORD commanded through Moses.' The submission of the entire counting to divine command mirrors Christ's own perfect submission to the Father's will in all things — every act of service grounded in obedience to God's word (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 5:19'>John 5:19</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 5:8'>Heb 5:8</a>).</p>",
    "38": "<p>The Gershonite count begins: those aged 30 to 50 who enter service. Together the three Levitical service groups — Kohath, Gershon, Merari — form a comprehensive body covering holy objects, fabric, and structural hardware. Christ's body likewise has many members with differing functions, all equally necessary (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Cor 12:12'>1 Cor 12:12</a>).</p>",
    "39": "<p>Gershon's enrollment by clans and families — 2,630 men. The organized, family-based structure of Levitical service anticipates the church as God's household (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 2:19'>Eph 2:19</a>) — not a collection of individuals but a family ordered under Christ, with assigned roles within a covenant community.</p>",
    "40": "<p>All Gershonites enrolled in service — as commanded. The repeated phrase 'as the LORD commanded Moses' underscores divine intentionality: every arrangement points forward to Christ, in whom every spiritual reality the tabernacle symbolized finds its true and lasting form (<a class='ref' data-ref='Col 2:17'>Col 2:17</a>).</p>",
    "41": "<p>Gershon count: 2,630 — recorded according to God's command. Numbers in God's service are not incidental; Christ similarly counts and weighs his servants with precision, declaring that even a cup of water given in his name will not go unrewarded (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 10:42'>Matt 10:42</a>).</p>",
    "42": "<p>The Merarite clans are enrolled — structural burden-bearers numbered by Moses and Aaron. Christ's work included bearing the full structural weight of human salvation — not visible glory-work but the foundational load of bearing the curse, upholding justice, and carrying the sin of the world (<a class='ref' data-ref='Isa 53:4'>Isa 53:4</a>).</p>",
    "43": "<p>Merari's service age range 30–50 applies uniformly. The consistency of God's standards across all service groups reflects the consistency of Christ's own call: the same Lord, the same faith, the same baptism for all who serve in his new-covenant household (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 4:5'>Eph 4:5</a>).</p>",
    "44": "<p>Merari count: 3,200 men — the largest of the three groups, as structural hardware outnumbers the more visible holy objects. The foundation-workers are most numerous. Christ's kingdom has many more who serve quietly in foundational ways than those who carry visible glory — and he honors them equally (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 20:26-27'>Matt 20:26–27</a>).</p>",
    "45": "<p>Merari's enrollment complete — as the LORD commanded through Moses. The structural hardware of the tabernacle carried by 3,200 men points to the vast number of those who in every generation have quietly upheld the church's structure: Christ sees every board-carrier and calls them his own.</p>",
    "46": "<p>Moses and Aaron and Israel's leaders count all the Levites appointed to service — the grand total of all three clans. Christ will at the last day render account for every servant entrusted to him: 'I have guarded them and not one of them has been lost' (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 17:12'>John 17:12</a>).</p>",
    "47": "<p>All who entered the service corps aged 30–50 for carrying and general service. The dual standard — carrying the objects (Kohath) and general transport service (Gershon, Merari) — suggests a distinction between those who carry the presence itself and those who carry the structure. Christ alone carries the divine presence; believers carry the gospel structure that makes his presence accessible.</p>",
    "48": "<p>Total enrolled: 8,580. The completeness of the count — every man in prime service years named and assigned — reflects God's total knowledge of his servants. Christ's declaration 'I know my own and my own know me' (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 10:14'>John 10:14</a>) is the new-covenant fulfillment of this meticulous enrollment.</p>",
    "49": "<p>Every man assigned his service and his load — as the LORD commanded Moses. The economy of God's service: no redundancy, no one left without a purpose, every load distributed according to divine wisdom. Christ assigns his own their work according to his will, promising that the yoke he assigns is easy and the burden light (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 11:29-30'>Matt 11:29–30</a>).</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>God commands Moses to send from the camp all who are leprous, or who have a discharge, or who are ceremonially unclean through contact with the dead — so the camp where God dwells is not defiled. Christ fulfills this paradoxically: he enters the uncleanness (touching lepers, the dead) and comes out clean, purifying rather than being defiled (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 8:3'>Matt 8:3</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='John 11:44'>John 11:44</a>).</p>",
    "2": "<p>The three categories of exclusion — <em>ṣāraʿat</em> (skin disease), discharge, corpse-contact — represent defilement by disease, bodily brokenness, and death. Christ takes all three categories upon himself: he touches the leper, the bleeding woman touches him, he raises the dead — reversing the flow of defilement, carrying all impurity into his own body on the cross (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Pet 2:24'>1 Pet 2:24</a>).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The exclusion applies to male and female alike — God's dwelling must remain holy because YHWH dwells in the midst of his people. Christ's sacrifice achieves what the expulsions only signaled: complete cleansing such that God now dwells permanently within his people through the Spirit (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Cor 6:19'>1 Cor 6:19</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 21:3'>Rev 21:3</a>).</p>",
    "4": "<p>Israel obeys, sending the unclean outside the camp as commanded. The camp outside the gate becomes the place of defilement — and it is precisely 'outside the gate' that Jesus suffers in order to sanctify the people through his own blood (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 13:12'>Heb 13:12</a>), voluntarily taking the place of the expelled.</p>",
    "5": "<p>When a man or woman commits any sin against another, they sin against YHWH. The vertical dimension of all sin — it is ultimately an offense against God — means that only divine forgiveness can truly resolve it. Christ atones not merely for social harms but for every sin as a covenant violation against the holy God (<a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 15:21'>Luke 15:21</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Ps 51:4'>Ps 51:4</a>).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The framework of <em>māʿal</em> (breach of faith against YHWH) reframes every ethical violation as theological treason. Christ's atoning work is correspondingly vast: he satisfies the full weight of every broken covenant obligation, restoring the relationship at its root rather than patching symptoms (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 9:15'>Heb 9:15</a>).</p>",
    "7": "<p>Confession of sin plus full restitution (<em>qeren</em>) plus the Levitical fifth — a 120% payment — is required. Christ's atonement is a perfect restitution that exceeds the debt: he not only pays what was owed but restores to the offended party richer than before, giving not just forgiveness but adoption and inheritance (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rom 8:17'>Rom 8:17</a>).</p>",
    "8": "<p>If the wronged party is dead with no kin-redeemer, the restitution goes to YHWH via the priest. Christ is the ultimate kinsman-redeemer who stands in when no one else can; as High Priest he alone can present the atoning payment that satisfies divine justice (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 7:25'>Heb 7:25</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='1 John 2:1-2'>1 John 2:1–2</a>).</p>",
    "9": "<p>Every sacred donation brought to the priest belongs to him — the Levitical principle that offerings for God pass through the mediating priest. Christ as the final mediating priest receives all that is offered to God in his name, presenting it perfected before the Father (<a class='ref' data-ref='1 Pet 2:5'>1 Pet 2:5</a>, believers offering spiritual sacrifices through Christ).</p>",
    "10": "<p>What each man gives to the priest is his own; what is consecrated belongs to the priest. The economy of holy giving — where offerings pass through priestly hands to God — is fulfilled in Christ who receives the sacrifices of his people and presents them holy and blameless to the Father (<a class='ref' data-ref='Col 1:22'>Col 1:22</a>).</p>",
    "11": "<p>God instructs Moses concerning the case of suspected marital unfaithfulness (the <em>sotah</em> procedure). The context of covenant jealousy — YHWH as the jealous husband of Israel — frames this ordinance within the larger typology of God's marriage covenant with his people, which Christ fulfills as the faithful bridegroom (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 5:25-27'>Eph 5:25–27</a>).</p>",
    "12": "<p>If a man's wife goes astray and acts treacherously — the language of marital betrayal echoes Israel's covenant infidelity toward YHWH. The prophets develop this into a full bridal metaphor: Israel/the church as wife, God/Christ as husband (<a class='ref' data-ref='Jer 3:1-3'>Jer 3:1–3</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Hos 2:2-20'>Hos 2:2–20</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 19:7'>Rev 19:7</a>).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The sin of unfaithfulness in secret, without witnesses — a hidden transgression that only the husband knows about. Christ as the bridegroom-judge sees all hidden sin; his eyes 'are like a flame of fire' (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 2:18'>Rev 2:18</a>). Yet he is also the husband who covers the shame of his bride through his blood (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 5:26-27'>Eph 5:26–27</a>).</p>",
    "14": "<p>The spirit of jealousy seizes the husband — whether his wife is guilty or not. The <em>qinʾâ</em> (jealousy/zeal) of God for covenant fidelity is fierce and just; it is the same zeal with which Jesus cleanses the temple and pursues his wayward people (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 2:17'>John 2:17</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Num 25:11'>Num 25:11</a>).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The husband brings his wife to the priest with a barley offering — the poor man's grain, without oil or frankincense, an offering of jealousy that brings iniquity to remembrance. Christ bears the full weight of covenant jealousy: he absorbs the wrath that the guilty deserve, presenting himself as the one who remembers sin in order to remove it (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 9:26'>Heb 9:26</a>).</p>",
    "16": "<p>The priest brings the woman before YHWH. The sotah procedure is explicitly coram Deo — before the face of God. Christ's atoning work is entirely in the presence of the Father: the Son presents himself and the sinner before the divine tribunal, interceding with his own blood as the testimony (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 9:24'>Heb 9:24</a>).</p>",
    "17": "<p>The priest takes holy water and dust from the tabernacle floor — a mixture of the sacred and the ordinary, the heavenly water and the earth itself. The incarnation is this mixture: the divine (holy water/Word) taking dust (human flesh) into union; the God-man is the ultimate blending of heaven and earth in one person (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 1:14'>John 1:14</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Gen 2:7'>Gen 2:7</a>).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The priest uncovers the woman's head while holding the bitter waters of the curse. The uncovering signifies vulnerability before divine judgment — the shame that belongs to the guilty. Christ was stripped and exposed before the crowd (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 27:28'>Matt 27:28</a>), bearing the shame of covenant-breakers in their place (<a class='ref' data-ref='Heb 12:2'>Heb 12:2</a>).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The priest adjures the woman: if you are innocent, these bitter waters will not harm you. The oath of innocence points to Christ who truly was innocent — and yet drank the bitter cup of God's wrath fully and willingly for the guilty (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 26:39'>Matt 26:39</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Isa 51:17'>Isa 51:17</a>).</p>",
    "20": "<p>If the woman has been unfaithful — the conditional that names the guilt. The language anticipates the New Testament's forensic framework: the guilty party must either bear the consequences or have them borne by another. Christ assumes the conditional guilt of his people, standing in as the condemned so they go free (<a class='ref' data-ref='2 Cor 5:21'>2 Cor 5:21</a>).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The priest invokes the curse oath: may YHWH make you a curse and an oath among your people, with thigh falling away and belly swollen. The covenant curse here reaches its ultimate expression in Christ who 'became a curse for us' on the cross (<a class='ref' data-ref='Gal 3:13'>Gal 3:13</a>), bearing the full embodied consequence of covenant infidelity in his crucified body.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The woman's amen-amen response to the curse seals her self-commitment to the ordeal's justice. Christ's own 'amen' responses throughout his ministry signify his full commitment to the truth of God's word — including the truth that curse falls on the sin-bearer (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 26:42'>Matt 26:42</a>).</p>",
    "23": "<p>The priest writes the curses and washes them into the bitter water — the ink of the written oath dissolved into the water the woman must drink. Paul's language of the debt-record (<em>cheirographon</em>) nailed to the cross echoes this: Christ dissolves the written indictment against us, absorbing the ink of condemnation into his own death (<a class='ref' data-ref='Col 2:14'>Col 2:14</a>).</p>",
    "24": "<p>The bitter water — water of cursing — is made to enter the woman so it brings bitter pain if guilty. The cup of God's wrath that Christ drinks in Gethsemane and on Calvary is this very cup: the distilled bitterness of divine judgment against covenant-breaking, poured into the innocent one's cup (<a class='ref' data-ref='Matt 26:39'>Matt 26:39</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Rev 14:10'>Rev 14:10</a>).</p>",
    "25": "<p>The priest waves the grain offering before YHWH and brings it to the altar. The grain offering alongside the bitter water creates a two-element ceremony — the ordinary (grain) alongside the extraordinary (bitter water). Christ's offering likewise joins his ordinary humanity (bread-like grain) to his extraordinary sacrifice (blood-and-curse-bearing) in one complete act.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The priest takes a handful of the grain as memorial portion and burns it on the altar; then makes the woman drink the water. The memorial offering (<em>ʾazkārâ</em>) is a token of the whole — just as Christ's Supper is the memorial of his whole sacrifice, a portion taken as the remembrance of the complete redemptive act (<a class='ref' data-ref='Luke 22:19'>Luke 22:19</a>).</p>",
    "27": "<p>If the woman is guilty, the water becomes bitter within her, bringing curse and public shame. If innocent, she is unharmed and will bear children. The twofold outcome — condemnation for the guilty, vindication and fruitfulness for the innocent — mirrors the eschatological judgment Christ brings: condemnation for the impenitent, life and fruitfulness for those united to him (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 3:18-19'>John 3:18–19</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='John 15:5'>John 15:5</a>).</p>",
    "28": "<p>The innocent woman is declared clean and shall conceive children. Fruitfulness follows vindication — the innocent wife's restored fertility reflects the church's fruitfulness after Christ's vindication and resurrection. The union between Christ and his church bears the fruit of new birth in the Spirit (<a class='ref' data-ref='John 15:16'>John 15:16</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Gal 4:26'>Gal 4:26</a>).</p>",
    "29": "<p>This is the law of jealousy — the full instruction for when the spirit of jealousy comes over a husband. The conclusion underscores that God is the covenant husband who authored this procedure; Christ as the jealous bridegroom who cleanses his church 'by the washing of water with the word' (<a class='ref' data-ref='Eph 5:26'>Eph 5:26</a>) is the antitype of this ordinance.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The principle applies whether the jealousy was justified or not — the ritual works either way, clearing the innocent and condemning the guilty. Christ's atonement covers all: he receives the guilty who flee to him and vindicates the innocent who rest in his righteousness, with the outcome perfectly corresponding to reality as God sees it (<a class='ref' data-ref='Rom 8:1'>Rom 8:1</a>).</p>",
    "31": "<p>The man is free from iniquity; the woman bears her own iniquity. The conclusion of the sotah law separates guilt properly — no innocent party bears what belongs to another. Yet Christ voluntarily assumes what does not belong to him, so that his people can be declared free with his own freedom. He bears iniquity that is not his; they receive innocence that is not theirs — the great exchange (<a class='ref' data-ref='2 Cor 5:21'>2 Cor 5:21</a>; <a class='ref' data-ref='Isa 53:11'>Isa 53:11</a>).</p>"
  }
}

